    en: "When a tenant is getting ready to move out, the landlord often wants to show the apartment to new renters. New York law requires reasonable notice before the landlord enters for a showing. Courts use 24 hours as the default baseline. The showing has to be at a reasonable time of day. The tenant does not have to allow showings at all hours or without warning. A lease can set specific terms, but a clause that gives the landlord unlimited access at any time usually cannot override the tenant's right to quiet enjoyment."
